Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

  1. PatientId: Uniqe identification of each patient
  2. AppointmentID: Unique identification of each appointment
  3. Gender: Male or Female
  4. ScheduledDay: The day the patient set up their appointment.
  5. Age: How old the patient is.
  6. Neighborhood: The location of the hospital.
  7. Scholarship: Indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  8. Hypertension: Whether a patient has it(True or False).
  9. Diabetes: Whether a patient has it(True or False).
  10. Alcoholism: Whether a patient has it(True or False).
  11. Handicap; Whether a patient is(True or False).
  12. SmsReceived: Messages sent to the patient.
  13. NoShow: Shows whether a patient showed up or not. Says No if the patient showed up to their appointment, and Yes if they did not show up.

Click here to view the dataset source.

Questions for Analysis¶

My questions for this dataset are split into two main areas of concern. How TIME and POPULATION play in this dataset.

Demography:

  1. Were there patients who missed appointments?
  2. What was the distribution like for appointment waiting times?
  3. What areas had the shortest and longest wait times?
  4. Timeframes with the highest and lowest appointments?
  5. Is there a correlation between the waiting time and no-show ups?
  6. What gender was most likely to miss and of what age?
  7. Which area was hit headest by patients who didn't show up?
  8. Which areas had the most and least appointments?
  9. Did the patients who received an sms(es) more likely show up?
  10. What factors correlate?

        x.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
        x.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
        x.spines['left'].set_visible(False)

    # Switch off ticks
        x.tick_params(axis="both", which="both", bottom="off", top="off", labelbottom="on", left="off", right="off", labelleft="on")

    # Draw horizontal axis lines
        vals = x.get_yticks()
        for tick in vals:
            x.axhline(y=tick, linestyle='dashed', alpha=0.4, color='#eeeeee', zorder=1)
            
    # Format y-axis label
        x.yaxis.set_major_formatter(StrMethodFormatter('{x:,g}'))
        ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
        ax.hist(x)
        ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
        ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)
        plt.show()

Creating a waiting-time category column based on conditions¶

This a breakdown of the waiting times based on category.

  • Same day = 0 Days
  • Short Wait = 1 to 3 Days
  • 1 Week = 4 to 7 Days
  • 2 Weeks = 8 to 15 Days
  • A Month = 16 to 30 Days
  • Quarter = 31 to 90 Days
  • Long Wait = 91 to 180 Days
  • Extreme Long Wait = 181 Days and Over
In [174]:
# Creating a list of conditions
conditions = [
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] == 0),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 1) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 3),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 4) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 7),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 8) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 15),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 16) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 30),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 31) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 90),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 91) & (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] <= 180),
    (df_noshow['WaitingTime'] >= 181)
     ]
               
# Creating a list of the category values to assign
values = ['Same day','Short Wait','1 Week','2 Weeks','A Month','Quarter','Long Wait','Extreme Long Wait']
               
#Create the waittime category
df_noshow['CategoryWT'] = np.select(conditions,values)

Conclusions¶

About 20% of the appointments made ended with the patients not turning up.

Looking at the waiting times, majority of appointments that happened on the scheduling day had the highest number of show up rates at about 34.9%. Same day appointments

MARUPE and SO CRISTVO had the longest waiting time.

As the waiting time increased so did the number of patients who didn't show up increase. However, the longest waiting time(between 90 and 180 days) did have an decrease in patients who didn't show up and this needs further investigation as to why this is the case.

More female patients were likely to miss showing up considered to their male counterparts.

The highest correlation was concetrated around hypertension and age, diabetes and hypertension, waiting time and sms received, diabetes and age.

Patients who received an sms were less likely to show up compared to those who didn't receive one according to the data. This needs some further investigation as we would think the opposite would be true since they are being reminded of their appointments. Also to check whether the same day appointment had an effect on this.

The neighborhood of Jardim Camburi recorded the highest missed appointments, the highest compared to the other neighborhoods.

Limitations¶

From the dataset provided, there are two columns that did seem swapped based on the dataset description. I am tempted to believe that the Handicap and SmsReceived values have been swapped based on boolean datatype in the description. However, due to the limited time I have to work on this I will not be investigating this further.

To make more meaning of the dataset, I think the dataset needed more features to further explain why the patients behaved the way they did.

Due to my limited expertise and time, I was not able to do some preditions using machine learning. I had some ideas on just using machine learning to do the analysis for me by predicting show-up rates and factors that carried heavy influence in predicting this.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and 
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
